[The number of fatal encephalitis cases reported continues to climb. On 18 Jun 2014, the count was 107 (see ProMED-mail archive no. 20140619.25) and now has climbed to 124 just 2 days later, as reported in [1] above and then to 130 mentioned in [2], another 2 days later. The nature of the vaccination campaign in report [2] is not mentioned but most likely is for Japanese encephalitis. However, Dr Jacob John dismisses JEV etiology in these early season AES cases (see ProMED-mail archive no. 20140615.2540893). He pointed out that the outbreaks in the Muzaffarpur district in Bihar state, annually recurrent, are quite different from many other outbreaks of JEV in various parts of India, including some parts of Bihar. He noted that JEV has a post-monsoon seasonality, obviously due to increase in _Culex_ mosquitoes that are vectors of JEV. Muzaffarpur outbreaks are during May-June (with some in April and some in July), and with onset of monsoon rains, the outbreak stops. The clinical and laboratory parameters of these cases in Bihar are not like encephalitis, rather, are typical of encephalopathy. It is not clear from the report [2] above whether the CDC will just test blood samples sent from India or whether CDC clinical team members will be involved in the field in Bihar as well, collaborating with Indian colleagues. Close collaboration between clinical staff attending affected patients and those providing laboratory support will be essential to arrive at a diagnosis.

Maps showing the location of Bihar State can be accessed at http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2558283,364. - Mod.TY

The low blood glucose levels suggest Reye's syndrome. This syndrome occurs in children who have been given aspirin when they have a viral illness, most commonly chickenpox or influenza. Infections with other viruses, such as parainfluenza, adenovirus, or enteroviruses are less commonly associated. Patients develop an acute encephalopathy and fatty liver and present with vomiting and altered mental status. Reye's syndrome or Reye-like syndrome has also been associated with exposure to other drugs or toxins. Blood ammonia levels are high, as are levels of alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and aspartate aminotransferase (AST). The mortality rate can be as high as 50 percent. - Mod.ML]
